# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gnss-positioning-deep
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] A DGPS system consists of networks of fixed position, ground-based reference stations.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] Each reference station calculates the difference between its highly accurate known position and its less accurate satellite-derived position.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] The stations broadcast this data locally—typically using ground-based transmitters of shorter range.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] Non-fixed (mobile) receivers use it to correct their position by the same amount, thereby improving their accuracy.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] Direct correction of position estimates is called *observation-space* correction.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] The United States Coast Guard (USCG) previously ran DGPS in the United States on longwave radio frequencies between 285 kHz and 325 kHz near major waterways and harbors.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] The USCG's DGPS was known as NDGPS (Nationwide DGPS) and was jointly administered by the Coast Guard and the Army Corps of Engineers.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] It consisted of broadcast sites located throughout the inland and coastal portions of the United States including Alaska, Hawaii and Puerto Rico.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] The Canadian Coast Guard (CCG) also ran a separate DGPS system, but discontinued its use on December 15, 2022.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] A similar system which transmits corrections from orbiting satellites instead of ground-based transmitters is called a satellite-based augmentation system.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] Although originally proposed under the name Wide-Area DGPS (WADGPS), it is actually a system that disseminates *state-space* correction including location-independent (satellite clock, ephemeris, health, etc.) and location-dependent (ionospheric delay) components.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] When GPS was first being put into service, the US military was concerned about the possibility of enemy forces using the globally available GPS signals to guide their own weapon systems.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] Originally, the government thought the "coarse acquisition" (C/A) signal would give only about 100-metre (330 ft) accuracy, but with improved receiver designs, the actual accuracy was 20 to 30 metres (66 to 98 ft).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] Starting in March 1990, to avoid providing such unexpected accuracy, the C/A signal transmitted on the L1 frequency (1575.42 MHz) was deliberately degraded by offsetting its clock signal by a random amount, equivalent to about 100 metres (330 ft) of distance.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] This technique, known as *Selective Availability*, or SA for short, seriously degraded the usefulness of the GPS signal for non-military users.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] More accurate guidance was possible for users of dual-frequency GPS receivers which also received the L2 frequency (1227.6 MHz), but the L2 transmission, intended for military use, was encrypted and was available only to authorized users with the decryption keys.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] This presented a problem for civilian users who relied upon ground-based radio navigation systems such as LORAN, VOR and NDB systems costing millions of dollars each year to maintain.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] The advent of a global navigation satellite system (GNSS) could provide greatly improved accuracy and performance at a fraction of the cost.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] The accuracy inherent in the SA however, was too poor to make this realistic.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] The military received multiple requests from the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA), United States Coast Guard (USCG) and United States Department of Transportation (DOT) to set SA aside to enable civilian use of GNSS, but remained steadfast in its objection on grounds of security.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] Throughout the early to mid 1980s, a number of agencies worked to develop a solution to the SA "problem".
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] Since the SA signal was changed slowly, the effect of its offset on positioning was relatively fixed – that is, if the offset was "100 meters to the east", that offset would be true over a relatively wide area.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] This suggested that broadcasting this offset to local GPS receivers could eliminate the effects of SA, resulting in measurements closer to GPS's theoretical performance, around 15 metres (49 ft).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] Additionally, another major source of errors in a GPS fix is due to transmission delays in the ionosphere, which could also be measured and corrected for in the broadcast.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] This offered an improvement to about 5 metres (16 ft) accuracy, more than enough for most civilian needs.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] The US Coast Guard was one of the more aggressive proponents of the DGPS, experimenting with the system on an ever-wider basis throughout the late 1980s and early 1990s.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] These signals are broadcast on marine longwave frequencies, which could be received on existing radiotelephones and fed into suitably equipped GPS receivers.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] Almost all major GPS vendors offered units with DGPS inputs, not only for the USCG signals, but also aviation units on either VHF or commercial AM radio bands.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] "Production quality" DGPS signals began to be sent out on a limited basis in 1996, and the network was rapidly expanded to cover most US ports of call, as well as the Saint Lawrence Seaway in partnership with the Canadian Coast Guard.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] Plans were put into place to expand the system across the US, but this would not be easy.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] The quality of the DGPS corrections generally fell with distance, and large transmitters capable of covering large areas tend to cluster near cities.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] This meant that lower-population areas, notably in the midwest and Alaska, would have little coverage by ground-based GPS.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] As of November 2013 the USCG's national DGPS consisted of 85 broadcast sites which provide dual coverage to almost the entire US coastline and inland navigable waterways including Alaska, Hawaii, and Puerto Rico.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] In addition the system provided single or dual coverage to a majority of the inland portion of United States.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] Instead, the FAA (and others) started studying broadcasting the signals across the entire hemisphere from communications satellites in geostationary orbit.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] This led to the Wide Area Augmentation System (WAAS) and similar systems, although these are generally not referred to as DGPS, or alternatively, "wide-area DGPS".
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] WAAS offers accuracy similar to the USCG's ground-based DGPS networks, and there has been some argument that the latter will be turned off as WAAS becomes fully operational.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] By the mid-1990s it was clear that the SA system was no longer useful in its intended role.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] DGPS would render it ineffective over the US, where it was considered most needed.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] Additionally, during the Gulf War of 1990–1991 SA had been temporarily turned off because Allied troops were using commercial GPS receivers.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] This showed that leaving SA turned off could be useful to the United States.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] In 2000, an executive order by President Bill Clinton turned it off permanently.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] Nevertheless, by this point DGPS had evolved into a system for providing more accuracy than even a non-SA GPS signal could provide on its own.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] There are several other sources of error which share the same characteristics as SA in that they are the same over large areas and for "reasonable" amounts of time.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] These include the ionospheric effects mentioned earlier, as well as errors in the satellite position ephemeris data and clock drift on the satellites.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] Depending on the amount of data being sent in the DGPS correction signal, correcting for these effects can reduce the error significantly, the best implementations offering accuracies of under 10 centimetres (3.9 in).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] In addition to continued deployments of the USCG and FAA sponsored systems, a number of vendors have created commercial DGPS services, selling their signal (or receivers for it) to users who require better accuracy than the nominal 15 meters GPS offers.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] Almost all commercial GPS units, even hand-held units, now offer DGPS data inputs, and many also support WAAS directly.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] To some degree, a form of DGPS is now a natural part of most GPS operations.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] A reference station calculates differential corrections for its own location and time.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] The correction data consists of the error in the calculated position of the station and/or the error in measured pseudorange calculated for each satellite.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] The correction data is distributed to users using radio or another method.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] A user acquires DGPS correction data stream (often a separate radio receiver, see § Networks below for how DGPS data is streamed) from a nearby station and combines it with GPS observations.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] Users may be up to 200 nautical miles (370 km) from the station.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] The basic use of DGPS is a simple setup where the correction data is applied to measurements in real-time.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] This is most commonly used in navigation of moving vehicles such as approaching aircraft and ships.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] In either case the calculation is straightforward.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] Real-time kinematic is a more advanced method.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] Instead of basic pseudorange (code phase) measurements, both the station and the receiver takes phase measurements of the GPS carrier wave to get a higher-resolution estimate of the pseudorange.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] The correction data is thus also of a higher resolution.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] Some components of the pseudorange or position (both *observation-space*) error vary with space: specifically, those introduced by satellite ephemeris errors and ionospheric and tropospheric distortions.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] For this reason, the accuracy of DGPS decreases with distance from the reference station.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] The problem can be aggravated if the user and the station lack "inter visibility"—when they are unable to see the same satellites: this is espcially bad if the correction is based on position.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] The positioning error grows approximately linearly with respect to the distance from the broadcast site.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] DGPS can refer to any type of differential augmentation system.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] The correction data can be transmitted to the receiver via ground radio stations (Ground-Based Augmentation System (GBAS)), satellite, and even through the Internet.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] Many airports run a short-range VHF radio service generally described as GBAS or LAAS for approaching aircraft.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] There used to be many nationwide ground-based broadcast systems: according to the US Coast Guard, 47 countries operated systems similar to the US NDGPS (Nationwide Differential Global Positioning System).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] A list can be found at the World DGPS Database for Dxers.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] European DGPS network has been developed mainly by the Finnish and Swedish maritime administrations in order to improve safety in the archipelago between the two countries.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] In the UK and Ireland, the system was implemented as a maritime navigation aid to fill the gap left by the demise of the Decca Navigator System in 2000.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] Transmitting on the 300-kHz band, the system underwent testing and two additional transmitters were added before the system was declared operational in 2002.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] The system was decommissioned in March 2022.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] Effective Solutions provides details and a map of European Differential Beacon Transmitters.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] The United States Department of Transportation, in conjunction with the Federal Highway Administration, the Federal Railroad Administration and the National Geodetic Survey appointed the United States Coast Guard as the maintaining agency for the U.S.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] The system is an expansion of the previous Maritime Differential GPS (MDGPS), which the Coast Guard began in the late 1980s and completed in March 1999.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] MDGPS covered only coastal waters, the Great Lakes, and the Mississippi River inland waterways, while NDGPS expands this to include complete coverage of the continental United States.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] The centralized Command and Control unit is the USCG Navigation Center, based in Alexandria, VA.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] There are currently 85 NDGPS sites in the US network, administered by the U.S.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] Department of Homeland Security Navigation Center.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] In 2015, the USCG and the United States Army Corps of Engineers (USACE) sought comments on a planned phasing-out of the U.S.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] In response to the comments received, a subsequent 2016 Federal Register notice announced that 46 stations would remain in service and "available to users in the maritime and coastal regions".
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] In spite of this decision, USACE decommissioned its remaining 7 sites and, in March 2018, the USCG announced that it would decommission its remaining stations by 2020.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] As of June 2020, all NDGPS service has been discontinued as it is no longer deemed a necessity owing to the removal of selective availability in 2000 and also the introduction of newer generation of GPS satellites.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] The Canadian system was similar to the US system and was primarily for maritime usage covering the Atlantic and Pacific coast as well as the Great Lakes and Saint Lawrence Seaway.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] It was discontinued as a service December 15, 2022.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] Australia runs two DGPS networks: one is mainly for marine navigation, broadcasting its signal on the long-wave band; another is used for land surveys and land navigation, and has corrections broadcast on the Commercial FM radio band.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] The marine DGPS service of 16 ground stations covering the Australian coast was discontinued effective July 1, 2020.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] Improved multichannel GPS capabilities, and signal sources from multiple providers (GPS, GLONASS, Galileo and BeiDou) was cited as providing better navigational accuracy than could be obtained from GPS + DGPS.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] An Australian Satellite-Based Augmentation System (SBAS), the Southern Positioning Augmentation Network (SouthPAN) offers higher accuracy positioning for GNSS users.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] The QZSS satellites operate a "sub-meter level augmentation system" (SLAS).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] It transmits pseudorange errors and satellite health information measured by 13 ground stations.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] It augments GPS, GLONASS, QZSS (itself), BeiDou, and Galileo.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] It uses the GPS L1 band, so existing receivers only require firmware modification to make use of it.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] Networked Transport of RTCM via Internet Protocol (NTRIP) is a standard Internet protocol for the exchange of GPS correction data, especially those pertaining to DGPS.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] Free and paid servers provide access to real-time correction data in this protocol.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] Some of them provide advanced features such as *virtual reference station*, where corrections from several nearby stations are combined to provide a better estimate of errors for the request location.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] NTRIP servers are extensively used in Real Time Kinematic work.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] Post-processing is used with Differential GPS to obtain precise positions of unknown points by relating them to known points such as survey markers.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] The GPS measurements are stored in the GPS receivers, and are subsequently transferred to a computer running the GPS post-processing software.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] The software computes baselines using simultaneous measurement data from two or more GPS receivers.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] The baselines represent a three-dimensional line drawn between the two points occupied by each pair of GPS antennas.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] The post-processed measurements allow more precise positioning, because most GPS errors affect each receiver nearly equally, and therefore can be cancelled out in the calculations.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] The improvement of GPS positioning doesn't require simultaneous measurements of two or more receivers in any case, but can also be done by special use of a *single* device.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/differential-gps] In the 1990s when even handheld receivers were quite expensive, some methods of quasi-differential GPS were developed, using the receiver in quick turns of positions or loops of 3-10 survey points.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] GPS signals include ranging signals, which are used to measure the distance to the satellite, and navigation messages.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The navigation messages include ephemeris data which are used both in trilateration to calculate the position of each satellite in orbit and also to provide information about the time and status of the entire satellite constellation, called the almanac.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] There are four GPS signal specifications designed for civilian use.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] In order of date of introduction, these are: L1 C/A, L2C, L5 and L1C.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] L1 C/A is also called the *legacy signal* and is broadcast by all currently operational satellites.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] L2C, L5 and L1C are *modernized signals* and are only broadcast by newer satellites (or not yet at all).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Furthermore, as of January 2021, none of these three signals are yet considered to be fully operational for civilian use.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] In addition to the four aforementioned signals, there are *restricted signals* with published frequencies and chip rates, but the signals use encrypted coding, restricting use to authorized parties.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Some limited use of restricted signals can still be made by civilians without decryption; this is called *codeless* and *semi-codeless* access, and this is officially supported.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The interface to the User Segment (GPS receivers) is described in the Interface Control Documents (ICD).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The format of civilian signals is described in the Interface Specification (IS) which is a subset of the ICD.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The GPS satellites (called *space vehicles* in the GPS interface specification documents) transmit simultaneously several ranging codes and navigation data using binary phase-shift keying (BPSK).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Only a limited number of central frequencies are used.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Satellites using the same frequency are distinguished by using different ranging codes.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] In other words, GPS uses code-division multiple access.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The ranging codes are also called *chipping codes* (in reference to CDMA/DSSS), *pseudorandom noise* (PRN) and *pseudorandom binary sequences* (in reference to the fact that the sequences are predictable yet that they statistically resemble noise).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Some satellites transmit several BPSK streams at the same frequency in quadrature, in a form of quadrature amplitude modulation.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] However, unlike typical QAM systems where a single bit stream is split into two, half-symbol-rate bit streams to improve spectral efficiency, the in-phase and quadrature components of GPS signals are modulated by separate (but functionally related) bit streams.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Satellites are uniquely identified by a serial number called *space vehicle number* (SVN) which does not change during its lifetime.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] In addition, all operating satellites are numbered with a *space vehicle identifier* (SV ID) and *pseudorandom noise number* (PRN number) which uniquely identifies the ranging codes that a satellite uses.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] There is a fixed one-to-one correspondence between SV identifiers and PRN numbers described in the interface specification.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Unlike SVNs, the SV ID/PRN number of a satellite may be changed (resulting in a change to the ranging codes it uses).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] That is, no two active satellites can share any one active SV ID/PRN number.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The current SVNs and PRN numbers for the GPS constellation are published at NAVCEN.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The original GPS design contains two ranging codes: the *coarse/acquisition* (C/A) code, which is freely available to the public, and the restricted *precision* (P) code, usually reserved for military applications.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] For the ranging codes and navigation message to travel from the satellite to the receiver, they must be modulated onto a carrier wave.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] In the case of the original GPS design, two frequencies are utilized; one at 1575.42 MHz (10.23 MHz × 154) called L1; and a second at 1227.60 MHz (10.23 MHz × 120), called L2.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The C/A code is transmitted on the L1 frequency as a 1.023 MHz signal using a bi-phase shift keying (BPSK) modulation technique.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The P(Y)-code is transmitted on both the L1 and L2 frequencies as a 10.23 MHz signal using the same BPSK modulation, however the P(Y)-code carrier is in quadrature with the C/A carrier (meaning it is 90° out of phase).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Besides redundancy and increased resistance to jamming, a critical benefit of having two frequencies transmitted from one satellite is the ability to measure directly, and therefore remove, the ionospheric delay error for that satellite.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Without such a measurement, a GPS receiver must use a generic model or receive ionospheric corrections from another source (such as the Wide Area Augmentation System or WAAS).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Advances in the technology used on both the GPS satellites and the GPS receivers has made ionospheric delay the largest remaining source of error in the signal.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] A receiver capable of performing this measurement can be significantly more accurate and is typically referred to as a *dual frequency receiver*.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The C/A PRN codes are Gold codes with a period of 1023 chips transmitted at 1.023 Mchip/s, causing the code to repeat every 1 millisecond.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] They are exclusive-ored with a 50 bit/s navigation message and the result phase modulates the carrier as previously described.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] These codes only match up, or strongly autocorrelate when they are almost exactly aligned.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Each satellite uses a unique PRN code, which does not correlate well with any other satellite's PRN code.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] In other words, the PRN codes are highly orthogonal to one another.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The 1 ms period of the C/A code corresponds to 299.8 km of distance, and each chip corresponds to a distance of 293 m.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Modern microcontrollers, even low cost ones, are able to measure phase angles well within 1% error.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] 1% of the given 1.023 Mchip/s results in approximately 10 nanoseconds.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Since GPS signals propagate at the speed of light, this represents a positional accuracy of about 3 Meters.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The C/A codes are generated by combining (using "exclusive or") two bit streams, each generated by two different maximal period 10 stage linear-feedback shift registers (LFSR).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Different codes are obtained by selectively delaying one of those bit streams.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] ; it is designated in the GPS interface specification.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The arguments of the functions therein are the number of *bits* or *chips* since their epochs, starting at 0.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The epoch of the LFSRs is the point at which they are at the initial state; and for the overall C/A codes it is the start of any UTC second plus any integer number of milliseconds.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The output of LFSRs at negative arguments is defined consistent with the period which is 1,023 chips (this provision is necessary because *B* may have a negative argument using the above equation).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The delay for PRN numbers 34 and 37 is the same; therefore their C/A codes are identical and are not transmitted at the same time (it may make one or both of those signals unusable due to mutual interference depending on the relative power levels received on each GPS receiver).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The P-code is a PRN sequence much longer than the C/A code: 6.187104 x 1012 chips.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Even though the P-code chip rate (10.23 Mchip/s) is ten times that of the C/A code, it repeats only once per week, eliminating range ambiguity.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] It was assumed that receivers could not directly acquire such a long and fast code so they would first "bootstrap" themselves with the C/A code to acquire the spacecraft ephemerides, produce an approximate time and position fix, and then acquire the P-code to refine the fix.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Whereas the C/A PRNs are unique for each satellite, each satellite transmits a different segment of a master P-code sequence approximately 2.35 x 1014 chips long (235,000,000,000,000 chips).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Each satellite repeatedly transmits its assigned segment of the master code, restarting every Sunday at 00:00:00 GPS time.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] For reference, the GPS epoch was Sunday January 6, 1980 at 00:00:00 UTC, but GPS does not follow UTC exactly because GPS time does not incorporate leap seconds.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Thus, GPS time is ahead of UTC by an integer (whole) number of seconds.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The P code is public, so to prevent unauthorized users from using or potentially interfering with it through spoofing, the P-code is XORed with *W-code*, a cryptographically generated sequence, to produce the *Y-code*.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The Y-code is what the satellites have been transmitting since the anti-spoofing module was enabled.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The encrypted signal is referred to as the *P(Y)-code*.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The details of the W-code are secret, but it is known that it is applied to the P-code at approximately 500 kHz, about 20 times slower than the P-code chip rate.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] This has led to semi-codeless and codeless approaches for tracking the P(Y) signal without knowing the W-code in extremely accurate civilian positioning, where it helps correct for ionospheric delay when combined with L1CA.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Unofficial use of L2P(Y) signals may be affected by future changes such as transmission power adjustments (potentially changing its phase).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] In 2008, the U.S. government agreed to not change the L2P(Y) phase until 2020.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The intent is to have civilian users migrate to the L2C code which provides an equivalent benefit.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] In addition to the PRN ranging codes, a receiver needs to know the time and position of each active satellite.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] GPS encodes this information into the *navigation message* and modulates it onto both the C/A and P(Y) ranging codes at 50 bit/s.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The navigation message format described in this section is called LNAV data (for *legacy navigation*).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] An ephemeris is valid for only four hours, while an almanac is valid–with little dilution of precision–for up to two weeks.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The receiver uses the almanac to acquire a set of satellites based on stored time and location.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] As the receiver acquires each satellite, each satellite’s ephemeris is decoded so that the satellite can be used for navigation.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The navigation message consists of 30-second *frames* 1,500 bits long, divided into five 6-second *subframes* of ten 30-bit words each.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Each subframe has the GPS time in 6-second increments.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Subframe 1 contains the GPS date (week number), satellite clock correction information, satellite status and satellite health.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Subframes 2 and 3 together contain the transmitting satellite's ephemeris data.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Subframes 4 and 5 together contain one *page* of the 25-page almanac.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The almanac is 15,000 bits long and the satellite takes 12.5 minutes to cycle through transmission of all 25 pages.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] A frame begins at the start of the GPS week and every 30 seconds thereafter.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Each week begins with the transmission of almanac page 1.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] There are two navigation message types: LNAV-L is used by satellites with PRN numbers 1 to 32 (called *lower PRN numbers*) and LNAV-U is used by satellites with PRN numbers 33 to 63 (called *upper PRN numbers*).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Subframes 1 to 3 are the same, while subframes 4 and 5 are almost the same.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Each message type contains almanac data for all satellites using the same navigation message type but not the other.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Each subframe begins with a Telemetry Word (TLM), which enables the receiver to detect the beginning of a subframe and determine the receiver clock time at which the navigation subframe begins.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Next is the handover word (HOW) giving the GPS time (as the time for when the first bit of the next subframe will be transmitted) and identifies the specific subframe within a complete frame.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The remaining eight words of the subframe contain the actual data specific to that subframe.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Each word includes 6 bits of parity generated using an algorithm based on Hamming codes, which take into account the 24 non-parity bits of that word and the last 2 bits of the previous word.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] After a subframe has been read and interpreted, the time the next subframe was sent can be calculated through the use of the clock correction data and HOW.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The receiver knows the receiver clock time of when the beginning of the next subframe was received from detection of the Telemetry Word thereby enabling computation of the transit time and thus the pseudorange.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] GPS time is expressed with a resolution of 1.5 seconds as a week number and a time of week count (TOW).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The TOW count is a value ranging from 0 to 403,199 whose meaning is the number of 1.5 second periods elapsed since the beginning of the GPS week.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Expressing TOW count thus requires 19 bits (219 = 524,288).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] GPS time is a continuous time scale in that it does not include leap seconds; therefore the start/end of GPS weeks may differ from that of the corresponding UTC day by an integer (whole) number of seconds.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] In each subframe, each hand-over word (HOW) contains the most significant 17 bits of the TOW count corresponding to the start of the next following subframe.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Note that the 2 least significant bits can be safely omitted because one HOW occurs in the navigation message every 6 seconds, which is equal to the resolution of the truncated TOW count thereof.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Equivalently, the truncated TOW count is the time duration since the last GPS week start/end to the beginning of the next frame in units of 6 seconds.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Each frame contains (in subframe 1) the 10 least significant bits of the corresponding GPS week number.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Note that each frame is entirely within one GPS week because GPS frames do not cross GPS week boundaries.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Since rollover occurs every 1,024 GPS weeks (approximately every 19.6 years; 1,024 is 210), a receiver that computes current calendar dates needs to deduce the upper week number bits or obtain them from a different source.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] One possible method is for the receiver to save its current date in memory when shut down, and when powered on, assume that the newly decoded truncated week number corresponds to the period of 1,024 weeks that starts at the last saved date.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] This method correctly deduces the full week number if the receiver is never allowed to remain shut down (or without a time and position fix) for more than 1,024 weeks (~19.6 years).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The *almanac* consists of coarse orbit and status information for each satellite in the constellation, an ionospheric model, and information to relate GPS derived time to Coordinated Universal Time (UTC).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Each frame contains a part of the almanac (in subframes 4 and 5) and the complete almanac is transmitted by each satellite in 25 frames total (requiring 12.5 minutes).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The first is to assist in the acquisition of satellites at power-up by allowing the receiver to generate a list of visible satellites based on stored position and time, while an ephemeris from each satellite is needed to compute position fixes using that satellite.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] In older hardware, lack of an almanac in a new receiver would cause long delays before providing a valid position, because the search for each satellite was a slow process.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Advances in hardware have made the acquisition process much faster, so not having an almanac is no longer an issue.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The second purpose is for relating time derived from the GPS (called GPS time) to the international time standard of UTC.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Finally, the almanac allows a single-frequency receiver to correct for ionospheric delay error by using a global ionospheric model.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The corrections are not as accurate as GNSS augmentation systems like WAAS or dual-frequency receivers.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] However, it is often better than no correction, since ionospheric error is the largest error source for a single-frequency GPS receiver.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Satellite data is updated typically every 24 hours, with up to 60 days data loaded in case there is a disruption in the ability to make updates regularly.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Typically the updates contain new ephemerides, with new almanacs uploaded less frequently.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The Control Segment guarantees that during normal operations a new almanac will be uploaded at least every 6 days.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Satellites broadcast a new ephemeris every two hours.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The ephemeris is generally valid for 4 hours, with provisions for updates every 4 hours or longer in non-nominal conditions.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Having reached full operational capability on July 17, 1995 the GPS system had completed its original design goals.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] However, additional advances in technology and new demands on the existing system led to the effort to "modernize" the GPS system.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Announcements from the Vice President and the White House in 1998 heralded the beginning of these changes, and in 2000, the U.S.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Congress reaffirmed the effort, referred to as *GPS III*.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The project involves new ground stations and new satellites, with additional navigation signals for both civilian and military users.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] It aims to improve the accuracy and availability for all users.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The implementation goal of 2013 was established, and contractors were offered incentives if they could complete it by 2011.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Modernized GPS civilian signals have two general improvements over their legacy counterparts: a dataless acquisition aid and forward error correction (FEC) coding of the NAV message.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] A dataless acquisition aid is an additional signal, called a pilot carrier in some cases, broadcast alongside the data signal.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] This dataless signal is designed to be easier to acquire than the data encoded and, upon successful acquisition, can be used to acquire the data signal.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] This technique improves acquisition of the GPS signal and boosts power levels at the correlator.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The second advancement is to use forward error correction (FEC) coding on the NAV message itself.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Due to the relatively slow transmission rate of NAV data (usually 50 bits per second), small interruptions can have potentially large impacts.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Therefore, FEC on the NAV message is a significant improvement in overall signal robustness.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] One of the first announcements was the addition of a new civilian-use signal, to be transmitted on a frequency other than the L1 frequency used for the coarse/acquisition (C/A) signal.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Ultimately, this became the L2C signal, so called because it is broadcast on the L2 frequency.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Because it requires new hardware on board the satellite, it is only transmitted by the so-called Block IIR-M and later design satellites.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The L2C signal is tasked with improving accuracy of navigation, providing an easy to track signal, and acting as a redundant signal in case of localized interference.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] L2C signals have been broadcast beginning in April 2014 on satellites capable of broadcasting it, but are still considered pre-operational.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] As of July 2023, L2C is broadcast on 25 satellites.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Unlike the C/A code, L2C contains two distinct PRN code sequences to provide ranging information; the *civil-moderate* code (called CM), and the *civil-long* length code (called CL).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The CM code is 10,230 chips long, repeating every 20 ms.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The CL code is 767,250 chips long, repeating every 1,500 ms.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Each signal is transmitted at 511,500 chips per second (chip/s); however, they are multiplexed together to form a 1,023,000-chip/s signal.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] CM is modulated with the CNAV Navigation Message (see below), whereas CL does not contain any modulated data and is called a *dataless sequence*.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The long, dataless sequence provides for approximately 24 dB greater correlation (~250 times stronger) than L1 C/A-code.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] When compared to the C/A signal, L2C has 2.7 dB greater data recovery and 0.7 dB greater carrier-tracking, although its transmission power is 2.3 dB weaker.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The civil-moderate and civil-long ranging codes are generated by a modular LFSR which is reset periodically to a predetermined initial state.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The period of the CM and CL is determined by this resetting and not by the natural period of the LFSR (as is the case with the C/A code).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The initial states are designated in the interface specification and are different for different PRN numbers and for CM/CL.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The feedback polynomial/mask is the same for CM and CL.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] mod is the remainder of division operation.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] or equivalently, since any GPS second (starting from 0).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Using this convention, the LFSR shifts from most significant bit to least significant bit and when seen in big endian order, it shifts to the right.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The states called *final state* in the IS are obtained after 10229 cycles for CM and after 767249 cycles for LM (just before reset in both cases).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The CNAV data is an upgraded version of the original NAV navigation message.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] It contains higher precision representation and nominally more accurate data than the NAV data.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The same type of information (time, status, ephemeris, and almanac) is still transmitted using the new CNAV format; however, instead of using a frame / subframe architecture, it uses a new pseudo-packetized format made of 12-second 300-bit *messages* analogous to LNAV frames.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] While LNAV frames have a fixed information content, CNAV messages may be of one of several defined types.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The type of a frame determines its information content.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Messages do not follow a fixed schedule regarding which message types will be used, allowing the Control Segment some versatility.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] However, for some message types there are lower bounds on how often they will be transmitted.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] In CNAV, at least 1 out of every 4 packets are ephemeris data and the same lower bound applies for clock data packets.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The design allows for a wide variety of packet types to be transmitted.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] With a 32-satellite constellation, and the current requirements of what needs to be sent, less than 75% of the bandwidth is used.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Only a small fraction of the available packet types have been defined; this enables the system to grow and incorporate advances without breaking compatibility.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] CNAV messages begin and end at start/end of GPS week plus an integer multiple of 12 seconds.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Specifically, the beginning of the first bit (with convolution encoding already applied) to contain information about a message matches the aforesaid synchronization.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] CNAV messages begin with an 8-bit preamble which is a fixed bit pattern and whose purpose is to enable the receiver to detect the beginning of a message.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] is the raw (non FEC encoded) navigation data, consisting of the simple concatenation of the 300-bit messages.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] navigation data bits elapsed since an arbitrary point in time (starting at 0).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Since the FEC encoded bit stream runs at 2 times the rate than the non FEC encoded bit as already described, then $t=\left\lfloor {\tfrac {t'}{2}}\right\rfloor$ .
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] FEC encoding is performed independently of navigation message boundaries; this follows from the above equations.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] An immediate effect of having two civilian frequencies being transmitted is the civilian receivers can now directly measure the ionospheric error in the same way as dual frequency P(Y)-code receivers.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] However, users utilizing the L2C signal alone, can expect 65% more position uncertainty due to ionospheric error than with the L1 signal alone.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] A major component of the modernization process is a new military signal (on L1M and L2M).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Called the Military code, or M-code, it was designed to further improve the anti-jamming and secure access of the military GPS signals.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Very little has been published about this new, restricted code.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] It contains a PRN code of unknown length transmitted at 5.115 MHz.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Unlike the P(Y)-code, the M-code is designed to be autonomous, meaning that a user can calculate their position using only the M-code signal.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] From the P(Y)-code's original design, users had to first lock onto the C/A code and then transfer the lock to the P(Y)-code.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Later, direct-acquisition techniques were developed that allowed some users to operate autonomously with the P(Y)-code.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] A little more is known about the new navigation message, which is called *MNAV*.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Similar to the new CNAV, this new MNAV is packeted instead of framed, allowing for very flexible data payloads.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Also like CNAV it can utilize Forward Error Correction (FEC) and advanced error detection (such as a CRC).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The M-code is transmitted in the same L1 and L2 frequencies already in use by the previous military code, the P(Y)-code.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The new signal is shaped to place most of its energy at the edges (away from the existing P(Y) and C/A carriers).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] It does not work at every satellite, and M-code was switched off for SVN62/PRN25 on 5 April 2011.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] In a major departure from previous GPS designs, the M-code is intended to be broadcast from a high-gain directional antenna, in addition to a full-Earth antenna.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] This directional antenna's signal, called a spot beam, is intended to be aimed at a specific region (several hundred kilometers in diameter) and increase the local signal strength by 20 dB, or approximately 100 times stronger.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] A side effect of having two antennas is that the GPS satellite will appear to be two GPS satellites occupying the same position to those inside the spot beam.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] While the whole Earth M-code signal is available on the Block IIR-M satellites, the spot beam antennas will not be deployed until the Block III satellites are deployed, which began in December 2018.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] An interesting side effect of having each satellite transmit four separate signals is that the MNAV can potentially transmit four different data channels, offering increased data bandwidth.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The modulation method is binary offset carrier, using a 10.23 MHz subcarrier against the 5.115 MHz code.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] This signal will have an overall bandwidth of approximately 24 MHz, with significantly separated sideband lobes.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The sidebands can be used to improve signal reception.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The L5 signal provides a means of radionavigation secure and robust enough for life critical applications, such as aircraft precision approach guidance.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The signal is broadcast in a frequency band protected by the ITU for aeronautical radionavigation services.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] It was first demonstrated from satellite USA-203 (Block IIR-M), and is available on all satellites from GPS IIF and GPS III.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] L5 signals have been broadcast beginning in April 2014 on satellites that support it.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The L5 band provides additional robustness in the form of interference mitigation, the band being internationally protected, redundancy with existing bands, geostationary satellite augmentation, and ground-based augmentation.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The added robustness of this band also benefits terrestrial applications.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Two PRN ranging codes are transmitted on L5 in quadrature: the in-phase code (called *I5-code*) and the quadrature-phase code (called *Q5-code*).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Both codes are 10,230 chips long, transmitted at 10.23 Mchip/s (1 ms repetition period), and are generated identically (differing only in initial states).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Then, I5 is modulated (by exclusive-or) with navigation data (called L5 CNAV) and a 10-bit Neuman-Hofman code clocked at 1 kHz.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Similarly, the Q5-code is then modulated but with only a 20-bit Neuman-Hofman code that is also clocked at 1 kHz.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The I5-code and Q5-code are generated using the same structure but with different parameters.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] These codes are the combination (by exclusive-or) of the output of 2 differing linear-feedback shift registers (LFSRs) which are selectively reset.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] a PRN number; both phases and a single PRN are required for the L5 signal from a single satellite.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The L5 CNAV data includes SV ephemerides, system time, SV clock behavior data, status messages and time information, etc.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The 50 bit/s data is coded in a rate 1/2 convolution coder.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The resulting 100 symbols per second (sps) symbol stream is modulo-2 added to the I5-code only; the resultant bit-train is used to modulate the L5 in-phase (I5) carrier.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] This combined signal is called the L5 Data signal.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The L5 quadrature-phase (Q5) carrier has no data and is called the L5 Pilot signal.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The format used for L5 CNAV is very similar to that of L2 CNAV.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] One difference is that it uses 2 times the data rate.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The bit fields within each message, message types, and forward error correction code algorithm are the same as those of L2 CNAV.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] L5 CNAV messages begin and end at start/end of GPS week plus an integer multiple of 6 seconds (this applies to the beginning of the first bit to contain information about a message, as is the case for L2 CNAV).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Broadcast on the L5 frequency (1176.45 MHz, 10.23 MHz × 115), which is an aeronautical navigation band.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The frequency was chosen so that the aviation community can manage interference to L5 more effectively than L2.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] L1C is a civilian-use signal, broadcast on the L1 frequency (1575.42 MHz), which contains the C/A signal used by all current GPS users.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The L1C signals broadcast from GPS III and later satellites, the first of which was launched in December 2018.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] As of 2024, L1C signals are broadcast, and only four operational satellites are capable of broadcasting them.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] L1C is expected on 24 GPS satellites in the late 2020s.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] L1C consists of a pilot (called L1CP) and a data (called L1CD) component.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] These components use carriers with the same phase (within a margin of error of 100 milliradians), instead of carriers in quadrature as with L5.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The PRN codes are 10,230 chips long and transmitted at 1.023 Mchip/s, thus repeating in 10 ms.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The pilot component is also modulated by an overlay code called L1CO (a secondary code that has a lower rate than the ranging code and is also predefined, like the ranging code).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Of the total L1C signal power, 25% is allocated to the data and 75% to the pilot.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The modulation technique used is BOC(1,1) for the data signal and TMBOC for the pilot.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The time multiplexed binary offset carrier (TMBOC) is BOC(1,1) for all except 4 of 33 cycles, when it switches to BOC(6,1).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The L1C pilot and data ranging codes are based on a Legendre sequence with length 10223 used to build an intermediate code (called a *Weil code*) which is expanded with a fixed 7-bit sequence to the required 10,230 bits.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] This 10,230-bit sequence is the ranging code and varies between PRN numbers and between the pilot and data components.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] ; it is introduced only to allow a more clear notation.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] According to the formula above and the GPS IS, the first $w_{i}$ bits (equivalently, up to the insertion point of S ) of ${\text{L1C}}'_{i}$ and ${\text{L1C}}$ are the first bits the corresponding Weil code; the next 7 bits are S ; the remaining bits are the remaining bits of the Weil code.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] For clarity, the formula for ${\text{L1C}}'_{i}$ does not account for the hypothetical case in which $p'_{i}>10\,222$ , which would cause the instance of S inserted into ${\text{L1C}}'_{i}$ to wrap from index 10229 to 0.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The overlay codes are 1,800 bits long and is transmitted at 100 bit/s, synchronized with the navigation message encoded in L1CD.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] For PRN numbers 1 to 63 they are the truncated outputs of maximal period LFSRs which vary in initial conditions and feedback polynomials.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The L1C navigation data (called CNAV-2) is broadcast in 1,800 bits long (including FEC) frames and is transmitted at 100 bit/s.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The frames of L1C are analogous to the messages of L2C and L5.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] While L2 CNAV and L5 CNAV use a dedicated message type for ephemeris data, all CNAV-2 frames include that information.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The common structure of all messages consists of 3 frames, as listed in the adjacent table.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The content of subframe 3 varies according to its page number which is analogous to the type number of L2 CNAV and L5 CNAV messages.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Pages are broadcast in an arbitrary order.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The time of messages (not to be confused with clock correction parameters) is expressed in a different format than the format of the previous civilian signals.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] An **interval time of week (ITOW):** the integer number of 2 hour periods elapsed since the latest start/end of week.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] It has range 0 to 83 (inclusive), requiring 7 bits to encode.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] A **time of interval (TOI):** the integer number of 18 second periods elapsed since the period represented by the current ITOW to the beginning of the *next* message.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] It has range 0 to 399 (inclusive) and requires 9 bits of data.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] The week number and ITOW are contained in subframe 2 along with other information.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Subframe 1 is encoded by a modified BCH code.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Specifically, the 8 least significant bits are BCH encoded to generate 51 bits, then combined using exclusive or with the most significant bit and finally the most significant bit is appended as the most significant bit of the previous result to obtain the final 52 bits.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p01] Subframes 2 and 3 are individually expanded with a 24-bit CRC, then individually encoded using a low-density parity-check code, and then interleaved as a single unit using a block interleaver.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] All satellites broadcast at the same two frequencies, 1.57542 GHz (L1 signal) and 1.2276 GHz (L2 signal).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] The satellite network uses a CDMA spread-spectrum technique where the low-bitrate message data is encoded with a high-rate pseudo-random noise (PRN) sequence that is different for each satellite.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] The receiver must be aware of the PRN codes for each satellite to reconstruct the actual message data.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] The C/A code, for civilian use, transmits data at 1.023 million chips per second, whereas the P code, for U.S. military use, transmits at 10.23 million chips per second.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] The L1 carrier is modulated by both the C/A and P codes, while the L2 carrier is only modulated by the P code.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] The P code can be encrypted as a so-called P(Y) code which is only available to military equipment with a proper decryption key.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] Both the C/A and P(Y) codes impart the precise time-of-day to the user.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] where $\scriptstyle P_{\operatorname {I} }$ and $\scriptstyle P_{\operatorname {Q} }$ represent signal powers; $\scriptstyle X_{\operatorname {I} }(t)$ and $\scriptstyle X_{\operatorname {Q} }(t)$ represent codes with/without data $\scriptstyle (=\;\pm 1)$ .
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] This is a formula for the ideal case (which is not attained in practice) as it does not model timing errors, noise, amplitude mismatch between components or quadrature error (when components are not exactly in quadrature).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] A GPS receiver processes the GPS signals received on its antenna to determine position, velocity and/or timing.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] The signal at antenna is amplified, down converted to baseband or intermediate frequency, filtered (to remove frequencies outside the intended frequency range for the digital signal that would alias into it) and digitalized; these steps may be chained in a different order.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] Note that aliasing is sometimes intentional (specifically, when undersampling is used) but filtering is still required to discard frequencies not intended to be present in the digital representation.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] For each satellite used by the receiver, the receiver must first **acquire** the signal and then **track** it as long as that satellite is in use; both are performed in the digital domain in by far most (if not all) receivers.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] Acquiring a signal is the process of determining the frequency and code phase (both relative to receiver time) when it was previously unknown.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] Code phase must be determined within an accuracy that depends on the receiver design (especially the tracking loop); 0.5 times the duration of code chips (approx.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] Tracking is the process of continuously adjusting the estimated frequency and phase to match the received signal as close as possible and therefore is a phase locked loop.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] Note that acquisition is performed to start using a particular satellite, but tracking is performed as long as that satellite is in use.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] In this section, one possible procedure is described for L1 C/A acquisition and tracking, but the process is very similar for the other signals.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] The described procedure is based on computing the correlation of the received signal with a locally generated replica of the ranging code and detecting the highest peak or lowest valley.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] The offset of the highest peak or lowest valley contains information about the code phase relative to receiver time.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] The duration of the local replica is set by receiver design and is typically shorter than the duration of navigation data bits, which is 20 ms.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] Acquisition of a given PRN number can be conceptualized as searching for a signal in a bidimensional search space where the dimensions are (1) code phase, (2) frequency.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] In addition, a receiver may not know which PRN number to search for, and in that case a third dimension is added to the search space: (3) PRN number.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] The frequency range of the search space is the band where the signal may be located given the receiver knowledge.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] varies by roughly 5 kHz due to the Doppler effect when the receiver is stationary; if the receiver moves, the variation is higher.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] The down conversion does not affect the frequency deviation; it only shifts all the signal frequency components down.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] Since the frequency is referenced to the receiver time, the uncertainty in the receiver oscillator frequency adds to the frequency range of the search space.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] The code gives strong autocorrelation only at offsets less than 1 in magnitude.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] The extent of the search space in the code phase dimension depends on the granularity of the offsets at which correlation is computed.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] It is typical to search for the code phase within a granularity of 0.5 chips or finer; that means 2,046 offsets.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] There may be more factors increasing the size of the search space of code phase.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] For example, a receiver may be designed so as to examine 2 consecutive windows of the digitalized signal, so that at least one of them does not contain a navigation bit transition (which worsens the correlation peak); this requires the signal windows to be at most 10 ms long.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] The lower PRN numbers range from 1 to 32 and therefore there are 32 PRN numbers to search for when the receiver does not have information to narrow the search in this dimension.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] The higher PRN numbers range from 33 to 66.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] If the almanac information has previously been acquired, the receiver picks which satellites to listen for by their PRNs.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] If the almanac information is not in memory, the receiver enters a search mode and cycles through the PRN numbers until a lock is obtained on one of the satellites.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] To obtain a lock, it is necessary that there be an unobstructed line of sight from the receiver to the satellite.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] The receiver can then decode the almanac and determine the satellites it should listen for.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] As it detects each satellite's signal, it identifies it by its distinct C/A code pattern.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] The simplest way to acquire the signal (not necessarily the most effective or least computationally expensive) is to compute the dot product of a window of the digitalized signal with a set of locally generated replicas.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] The locally generated replicas vary in carrier frequency and code phase to cover all the already mentioned search space which is the Cartesian product of the frequency search space and the code phase search space.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] The carrier is a complex number where real and imaginary components are both sinusoids as described by Euler's formula.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] The replica that generates the highest magnitude of dot product is likely the one that best matches the code phase and frequency of the signal; therefore, if that magnitude is above a threshold, the receiver proceeds to track the signal or further refine the estimated parameters before tracking.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] The threshold is used to minimize false positives (apparently detecting a signal when there is in fact no signal), but some may still occur occasionally.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] Using a complex carrier allows the replicas to match the digitalized signal regardless of the signal's carrier phase and to detect that phase (the principle is the same used by the Fourier transform).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] The dot product is a complex number; its magnitude represents the level of similarity between the replica and the signal, as with an ordinary correlation of real-valued time series.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] The argument of the dot product is an approximation of the corresponding carrier in the digitalized signal.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] As an example, assume that the granularity for the search in code phase is 0.5 chips and in frequency is 500 Hz, then there are **1,023/0.5 = 2,046 code phases** and **10,000 Hz/500 Hz = 20 frequencies** to try for a total of **20×2,046 = 40,920 local replicas**.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] Note that each frequency bin is centered on its interval and therefore covers 250 Hz in each direction; for example, the first bin has a carrier at −4.750 Hz and covers the interval −5,000 Hz to −4,500 Hz.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] Code phases are equivalent modulo 1,023 because the ranging code is periodic; for example, phase −0.5 is equivalent to phase 1,022.5.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] The following table depicts the local replicas that would be compared against the digitalized signal in this example.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] As an improvement over the simple correlation method, it is possible to implement the computation of dot products more efficiently with a Fourier transform.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] Specifically, for all code phases in the search space, the digitalized signal window is multiplied element by element with a local replica of the code (with no carrier), then processed with a discrete Fourier transform.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] Given the previous example to be processed with this method, assume real-valued data (as opposed to complex data, which would have in-phase and quadrature components), a sampling rate of 5 MHz, a signal window of 10 ms, and an intermediate frequency of 2.5 MHz.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] Only the components (or bins) within 5 kHz of the central frequency are examined, which is the range from 2.495 MHz to 2.505 MHz, and it is covered by **51 frequency components**.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] There are **2,046 code phases** as in the previous case, thus in total **51×2,046 = 104,346 complex frequency components** will be examined.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] Likewise, as an improvement over the simple correlation method, it is possible to perform a single operation covering all code phases for each frequency bin.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] The operation performed for each code phase bin involves forward FFT, element-wise multiplication in the frequency domain. inverse FFT, and extra processing so that overall, it computes circular correlation instead of circular convolution.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] This yields more accurate *code phase determination* than the simple correlation method in contrast with the previous method, which yields more accurate *carrier frequency determination* than the previous method.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] Since the carrier frequency received can vary due to Doppler shift, the points where received PRN sequences begin may not differ from O by an exact integral number of milliseconds.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] Because of this, carrier frequency tracking along with PRN code tracking are used to determine when the received satellite's PRN code begins.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] Unlike the earlier computation of offset in which trials of all 1,023 offsets could potentially be required, the tracking to maintain lock usually requires shifting of half a pulse width or less.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] To perform this tracking, the receiver observes two quantities, phase error and received frequency offset.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] The correlation of the received PRN code with respect to the receiver generated PRN code is computed to determine if the bits of the two signals are misaligned.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] Comparisons of the received PRN code with receiver generated PRN code shifted half a pulse width early and half a pulse width late are used to estimate adjustment required.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] The amount of adjustment required for maximum correlation is used in estimating phase error.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] Received frequency offset from the frequency generated by the receiver provides an estimate of phase rate error.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] The command for the frequency generator and any further PRN code shifting required are computed as a function of the phase error and the phase rate error in accordance with the control law used.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] The Doppler velocity is computed as a function of the frequency offset from the carrier nominal frequency.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] The Doppler velocity is the velocity component along the line of sight of the receiver relative to the satellite.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] As the receiver continues to read successive PRN sequences, it will encounter a sudden change in the phase of the 1,023-bit received PRN signal.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] This indicates the beginning of a data bit of the navigation message.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] This enables the receiver to begin reading the 20 millisecond bits of the navigation message.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] The TLM word at the beginning of each subframe of a navigation frame enables the receiver to detect the beginning of a subframe and determine the receiver clock time at which the navigation subframe begins.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] The HOW word then enables the receiver to determine which specific subframe is being transmitted.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] There can be a delay of up to 30 seconds before the first estimate of position because of the need to read the ephemeris data before computing the intersections of sphere surfaces.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] After a subframe has been read and interpreted, the time the next subframe was sent can be calculated through the use of the clock correction data and the HOW.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] The receiver is potentially capable of getting a new pseudorange measurement at the beginning of each subframe or every 6 seconds.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] Then the orbital position data, or ephemeris, from the navigation message is used to calculate precisely where the satellite was at the start of the message.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/gps-signals-p02] A more sensitive receiver will potentially acquire the ephemeris data more quickly than a less sensitive receiver, especially in a noisy environment.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/multilateration] The distances or ranges might be ordinary Euclidean distances (slant ranges) or spherical distances (scaled central angles), as in *true-range multilateration*; or biased distances (pseudo-ranges), as in *pseudo-range multilateration*.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/multilateration] Trilateration or multilateration should not be confused with *triangulation*, which uses angles for positioning; and *direction finding*, which determines the line of sight direction to a target without determining the radial distance.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/multilateration] Multiple, sometimes overlapping and conflicting terms are employed for similar concepts – e.g., *multilateration* without modification has been used for aviation systems employing both true-ranges and pseudo-ranges.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/multilateration] Moreover, different fields of endeavor may employ different terms.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/multilateration] In geometry, *trilateration* is defined as the process of determining absolute or relative locations of points by measurement of distances, using the geometry of circles, spheres or triangles.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/multilateration] In surveying, *trilateration* is a specific technique.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/multilateration] Energy waves may be involved in determining range, but are not required.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/multilateration] True-range multilateration is both a mathematical topic and an applied technique used in several fields.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/multilateration] A practical application involving a fixed location occurs in surveying.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/multilateration] Applications involving vehicle location are termed navigation when on-board persons/equipment are informed of its location, and are termed surveillance when off-vehicle entities are informed of the vehicle's location.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/multilateration] Two *slant ranges* from two known locations can be used to locate a third point in a two-dimensional Cartesian space (plane), which is a frequently applied technique (e.g., in surveying).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/multilateration] Similarly, two *spherical ranges* can be used to locate a point on a sphere, which is a fundamental concept of the ancient discipline of celestial navigation — termed the *altitude intercept* problem.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/multilateration] Moreover, if more than the minimum number of ranges are available, it is good practice to utilize those as well.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/multilateration] This article addresses the general issue of position determination using multiple ranges.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/multilateration] In two-dimensional geometry, it is known that if a point lies on two circles, then the circle centers and the two radii provide sufficient information to narrow the possible locations down to two – one of which is the desired solution and the other is an ambiguous solution.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/multilateration] Additional information often narrow the possibilities down to a unique location.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/multilateration] In three-dimensional geometry, when it is known that a point lies on the surfaces of three spheres, then the centers of the three spheres along with their radii also provide sufficient information to narrow the possible locations down to no more than two (unless the centers lie on a straight line).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/multilateration] True-range multilateration can be contrasted to the more frequently encountered pseudo-range multilateration, which employs range differences to locate a (typically, movable) point.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/multilateration] Pseudo range multilateration is almost always implemented by measuring times-of-arrival (TOAs) of energy waves.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/multilateration] True-range multilateration can also be contrasted to triangulation, which involves the measurement of angles.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/multilateration] TOFs are biased by synchronization errors in the difference between *times of arrival* (TOA) and *times of transmission* (TOT): TOF = TOA − TOT.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/multilateration] *Pseudo-ranges* (PRs) are TOFs multiplied by the wave propagation speed: PR = TOF·*s*.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/multilateration] In general, the stations' clocks are assumed synchronized but the vehicle's clock is desynchronized.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/multilateration] In MLAT for surveillance, the waves are transmitted by the vehicle and received by the stations; the TOT is unique and unknown, while the TOAs are multiple and known.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/multilateration] When MLAT is used for navigation (as in *hyperbolic navigation*), the waves are transmitted by the stations and received by the vehicle; in this case, the TOTs are multiple but known, while the TOA is unique and unknown.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/multilateration] In navigation applications, the vehicle is often termed the "user"; in surveillance applications, the vehicle may be termed the "target".
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/multilateration] The vehicle's clock is considered an additional unknown, to be estimated along with the vehicle's position coordinates.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/multilateration] If d is the number of physical dimensions being considered (e.g., 2 for a plane) and m is the number of signals received (thus, TOFs measured), it is required that $m\geq d+1$ .
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/multilateration] Processing is usually required to extract the TOAs or their differences from the received signals, and an algorithm is usually required to solve this set of equations.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/multilateration] An algorithm either: (a) determines numerical values for the TOT (for the receiver(s) clock) and d vehicle coordinates; or (b) ignores the TOT and forms $m-1$ (at least d) time difference of arrivals (TDOAs), which are used to find the d vehicle coordinates.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/multilateration] Almost always, $d=2$ (e.g., a plane or the surface of a sphere) or $d=3$ (e.g., the real physical world).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/multilateration] Systems that form TDOAs are also called *hyperbolic* systems, for reasons discussed below.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/multilateration] A multilateration *navigation* system provides vehicle position information to an entity "on" the vehicle (e.g., aircraft pilot or Global Positioning System (GPS) receiver operator).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/multilateration] A multilateration *surveillance* system provides vehicle position to an entity "not on" the vehicle (e.g., air traffic controller or cell phone provider).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/multilateration] By the reciprocity principle, any method that can be used for navigation can also be used for surveillance, and vice versa (the same information is involved).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/multilateration] Systems have been developed for both TOT and TDOA (which ignore TOT) algorithms.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/multilateration] In this article, TDOA algorithms are addressed first, as they were implemented first.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/multilateration] Due to the technology available at the time, TDOA systems often determined a vehicle location in two dimensions.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/multilateration] They were implemented, roughly, post-1975 and usually involve satellites.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/multilateration] Due to technology advances, TOT algorithms generally determine a user/vehicle location in three dimensions.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/multilateration] However, conceptually, TDOA or TOT algorithms are not linked to the number of dimensions involved.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/precise-point-positioning] PPP relies on two general sources of information: direct observables and ephemerides.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/precise-point-positioning] Direct observables are data that the GPS receiver can measure on its own.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/precise-point-positioning] All GPS devices measure the **signal phase** using the timing message encoded in the GNSS signal.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/precise-point-positioning] One additional direct observable for PPP is **carrier phase**, i.e., whether the wave of that signal is going "up" or "down" at a given moment.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/precise-point-positioning] Loosely speaking, phase can be thought of as the digits after the decimal point in the number of waves between a given GNSS satellite and the receiver.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/precise-point-positioning] The smaller wavelength of the carrier (roughly 20 cm) allows for more precise tracking of pseudorange.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/precise-point-positioning] However, the carrier does not include information about how many carrier-cycles have actually elapsed, so there exists an **integer ambiguity problem** (IAP) to be solved.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/precise-point-positioning] In PPP, continuous observation is used to generate enough data for a statistical resolution of the IAP.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/precise-point-positioning] Another important additional direct observable is the **differential delay** between GNSS signals of different frequencies.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/precise-point-positioning] This is useful because a major source of position error is variability in how GNSS signals are slowed in the ionosphere, which is affected relatively unpredictably by space weather.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/precise-point-positioning] The ionosphere is dispersive, meaning that signals of different frequency are slowed by different amounts.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/precise-point-positioning] By measuring the difference in the delays between signals of different frequencies, the receiver software (or later post-processing) can model and remove the delay at any frequency.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/precise-point-positioning] This process is only approximate, and non-dispersive sources of delay remain (notably from water vapor moving around in the troposphere), but it improves accuracy significantly.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/precise-point-positioning] For single-frequency receivers, real-time ionospheric correction may be achieved by downloading electron content (TEC) maps from GDGPS or IGS.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/precise-point-positioning] Precision is worse compared to the dual-frequency case.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/precise-point-positioning] Ephemerides are precise measurements of the GNSS satellites' orbits, made by the geodetic community (the International GNSS Service and other public and private organizations) with global networks of ground stations.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/precise-point-positioning] Satellite navigation works on the principle that the satellites' positions at any given time are known, but in practice, micrometeoroid impacts, variation in solar radiation pressure, and so on mean that orbits are not perfectly predictable.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/precise-point-positioning] The ephemerides that the satellites broadcast are earlier forecasts, up to a few hours old, and are less accurate (by up to a few meters) than carefully processed observations of where the satellites actually were.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/precise-point-positioning] Therefore, if a GNSS receiver system stores raw observations, they can be processed later against a more accurate ephemeris than what was in the GNSS messages, yielding more accurate position estimates than what would be possible with standard realtime calculations.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/precise-point-positioning] This post-processing technique has long been standard for GNSS applications that need high accuracy.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/precise-point-positioning] The International GNSS Service (IGS) uses its global network of monitoring stations to produce higher-accuracy ephemerides and clock drift data for the GPS satellites.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/precise-point-positioning] The IGS produces and archives the coarse estimates broadcast by the satellites, a finer ultra-rapid observation and prediction published four times per day (~5 cm), an even finer "rapid" data from daily post-processing (~2.5 cm), and the finest "final" data published weekly (~2.5 cm).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/precise-point-positioning] The ultra-rapid prediction can be used in real time to obtain higher-accuracy results.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/precise-point-positioning] The other data can be used on recorded GPS data to produce even better-accuracy results after the fact.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/precise-point-positioning] Weekly final ephemerides are offered for GLONASS.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/precise-point-positioning] Data pipelines for additional GNSS systems are still being tested.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/precise-point-positioning] NASA JPL operates the Global Differential GPS (GDGPS) system using a global network of stations.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/precise-point-positioning] GDGPS disseminates real-time orbit (once per second, latency ~5 seconds; accuracy ~20 cm) and clock corrections and supports a wider range of GNSS networks beyond GPS (GLONASS, BeiDou, Galileo, and QZSS).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/precise-point-positioning] GDGPS feeds into APPS (Automatic Precise Positioning Service) of JPL, which uses these streams to apply in near realtime the same kind of correction that used to be done in post-processing.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/precise-point-positioning] NASA JPL also produces higher-latency but also higher-accuracy "ultra-rapid", "rapid", and "final" orbit and clock values for the GPS constellation through its GipsyX service, a service quite similar to its IGS counterpart.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/precise-point-positioning] Between the sender and receiver there tends to be some phase bias not accounted for by ephermeris and clock corrections, caused directly by the radio hardware.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/precise-point-positioning] This bias is responsible for most of the IAP problem.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/precise-point-positioning] In PPP-AR (ambiguity resolution), a bias value is provided for each satellite in addition to the ephermeris and clock corrections.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/precise-point-positioning] PPP-RTK combines PPP-AR with location-dependent information (ionosphere and troposheric corrections) from a base station.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/precise-point-positioning] When close to the base station, it fixes as fast as real-time kinematic positioning.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/precise-point-positioning] When further away, it still provides a boost in time-to-first-fix and accuracy relative to plain PPP.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/precise-point-positioning] ICAO-compliant satellite-based augmentation systems (SBASs) include near-real-time ionospheric delay, ephemerides, and clock drift information for aviation use.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/precise-point-positioning] An example is European Geostationary Navigation Overlay Service.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/precise-point-positioning] There are also SBASs explicitly designed for PPP: CLAS and MADOCA-PPP of Quasi-Zenith Satellite System, PVS of Southern Positioning Augmentation Network, and HAS of Galileo.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/precise-point-positioning] Higher-precision, "final" ionospheric and troposheric delay data can also be obtained from the IGS for later re-analysis.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/precise-point-positioning] Precise positioning is increasingly used in the fields including robotics, autonomous navigation, agriculture, construction, and mining.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/precise-point-positioning] The major weaknesses of PPP, compared with conventional consumer GNSS methods, are that it takes more processing power, it requires an outside ephemeris correction stream, and it takes some time (up to tens of minutes) to converge to full accuracy.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/precise-point-positioning] This makes it relatively unappealing for applications such as fleet tracking, where centimeter-scale precision is generally not worth the extra complexity, and more useful in areas like robotics, where there may already be an assumption of onboard processing power and frequent data transfer.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/precise-point-positioning] NASA JPL operates the Automatic Precise Positioning Service (APPS), a free on-line service that turns GNSS recordings into PPP-determined positions.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/precise-point-positioning] It is supported by a fleet of dedicated computers running the GipsyX/RTGX software.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/real-time-kinematic-positioning] The distance between a satellite navigation receiver and a satellite can be calculated from the time it takes for a signal to travel from the satellite to the receiver.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/real-time-kinematic-positioning] To calculate the delay, the receiver must align a pseudorandom binary sequence contained in the signal to an internally generated pseudorandom binary sequence.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/real-time-kinematic-positioning] Since the satellite signal takes time to reach the receiver, the satellite's sequence is delayed in relation to the receiver's sequence.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/real-time-kinematic-positioning] By increasingly delaying the receiver's sequence, the two sequences are eventually aligned.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/real-time-kinematic-positioning] RTK follows the same general concept, but uses the satellite signal's carrier wave as its signal, ignoring the information contained within.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/real-time-kinematic-positioning] RTK uses a fixed *base station* and a *rover* to reduce the *rover's* position error.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/real-time-kinematic-positioning] For this purpose, the *base station* transmits correction data to the rover.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/real-time-kinematic-positioning] As described in the previous section, the range to a satellite is essentially calculated by multiplying the carrier wavelength with the number of whole carrier cycles between the satellite and the rover and adding the phase difference.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/real-time-kinematic-positioning] Determining the number of cycles is non-trivial, since signals may be shifted in phase by one or more cycles.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/real-time-kinematic-positioning] This results in an error equal to the error in the estimated number of cycles times the wavelength, which is 19 cm for the L1 signal.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/real-time-kinematic-positioning] Solving this so-called **integer ambiguity search** problem results in centimeter precision.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/real-time-kinematic-positioning] The error can be reduced with sophisticated statistical methods that compare the measurements from the C/A signals and by comparing the resulting ranges between multiple satellites.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/real-time-kinematic-positioning] If a nearby base station measures the bias for the rover, the rover can forgo the more complex calculation.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/real-time-kinematic-positioning] The improvement possible using this technique is potentially very high if one continues to assume a 1% accuracy in locking.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/real-time-kinematic-positioning] For instance, in the case of GPS, the coarse-acquisition (C/A) code, which is broadcast in the L1 signal, changes phase at 1.023 MHz, but the L1 carrier itself is 1575.42 MHz, which changes phase over a thousand times more often.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/real-time-kinematic-positioning] A ±1% error in L1 carrier-phase measurement thus corresponds to a ±1.9 mm error in baseline estimation.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/real-time-kinematic-positioning] In practice, RTK systems use a single base-station receiver and a number of mobile units.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/real-time-kinematic-positioning] The base station re-broadcasts the phase of the carrier that it observes, and the mobile units compare their own phase measurements with the one received from the base station.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/real-time-kinematic-positioning] There are several ways to transmit a correction signal from base station to mobile station.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/real-time-kinematic-positioning] The most popular way to achieve real-time, low-cost signal transmission is to use a radio modem, typically in the UHF Band.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/real-time-kinematic-positioning] In most countries, certain frequencies are allocated specifically for RTK purposes.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/real-time-kinematic-positioning] Most land-survey equipment has a built-in UHF-band radio modem as a standard option.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/real-time-kinematic-positioning] RTK provides accuracy enhancements up to about 20 km from the base station.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/real-time-kinematic-positioning] This allows the units to calculate their *relative* position to within millimeters, although their absolute position is accurate only to the same accuracy as the computed position of the base station.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/real-time-kinematic-positioning] For RTK with a single base station, accuracy of 8mm + 1ppm (parts per million / 1mm per km) horizontal and 15mm + 1ppm vertical relative to the base station can be achieved, depending on the device.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/real-time-kinematic-positioning] For example, with a base station 16 km (slightly less than 10 miles) away, relative horizontal error would be 8mm + 16mm = 24mm (slightly less than an inch).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/real-time-kinematic-positioning] Although these parameters limit the usefulness of the RTK technique for general navigation, the technique is perfectly suited to roles like surveying.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/real-time-kinematic-positioning] In this case, the base station is located at a known surveyed location, often a benchmark, and the mobile units can then produce a highly accurate map by taking fixes relative to that point.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/real-time-kinematic-positioning] RTK has also found uses in autodrive/autopilot systems, precision farming, machine control systems and similar roles.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/real-time-kinematic-positioning] A **Continuously Operating Reference Station** is a station that continuously broadcast corrections, usually over an Internet connection.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/real-time-kinematic-positioning] A typical CORS setup consists of a single reference station from which the raw data (or corrections) are sent to the rover receiver (i.e., the user).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/real-time-kinematic-positioning] The user then forms the carrier phase differences (or corrects their raw data) and performs the data processing using the differential corrections.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/real-time-kinematic-positioning] Accuracy is increased in a CORS network, because more than one station helps ensure correct positioning and guards against a false initialization of a single base station.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/real-time-kinematic-positioning] A **virtual reference station** (VRS) is a simulated reference station, most commonly from combining multiple nearby stations in the same network to estimate what the corrections would be near at the user's position, reducing the apparent baseline length.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/real-time-kinematic-positioning] Using a VRS helps improve accuracy when the nearest reference station is too far away (e.g. > 50 km) for successful ambiguity resolution with standard RTK.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/real-time-kinematic-positioning] PPP-RTK, also known as SSR-RTK is a combination of RTK with techniques from precise point positioning (PPP).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/real-time-kinematic-positioning] PPP-RTK/SSR-RTK combines the globally applicable corrections from PPP-AR with location-dependent information (ionosphere and troposheric corrections) from a base station.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/real-time-kinematic-positioning] As a result, it obtains position fixes as quickly as RTK when near the base station.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/real-time-kinematic-positioning] When further away from the base station, it acts as a faster and more accurate version of PPP.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-based-augmentation-system] ICAO material describes SBAS as a wide-coverage GNSS augmentation system in which the user receives correction and integrity information from a satellite-based transmitter, with Standards and Recommended Practices (SARPs) for SBAS included in Annex 10.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-based-augmentation-system] This Annex describes a standard data format for use in aviation as well as their broadcast on L1 (and more recently L5).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-based-augmentation-system] Many SBAS satellites also provide their own timing/ranging signals, acting as additional satellites for positioning.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-based-augmentation-system] Using measurements from the ground stations, *state-space* correction messages are created and sent to one or more satellites for broadcast to end users as differential signal.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-based-augmentation-system] These correction messages include separate values for location-independent corrections (satellite clock, ephemeris, health, etc.) and location-dependent corrections (ionospheric delay).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-based-augmentation-system] The idea of SBAS was first proposed in 1991 as "wide-area differential GPS" (WADGPS), but unlike typical DGPS, WADGPS and many later SBAS implementations provide *state-space* as opposed to *observation-space* corrections consisting of location or pseudorange errors at specific stations.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-based-augmentation-system] A few online services provide access to the data broadcast by SBAS satellites via the Internet, which is useful in areas of low SBAS visibility (e.g. unmanned aerial vehicles navigating urban canyons).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-based-augmentation-system] Some services such as International GNSS Service (IGS) provide direct access to predicted orbit and clock corrections for GPS (covering a couple of hours).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-based-augmentation-system] Networked Transport of RTCM via Internet Protocol is an internet protocol for access to such data.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-based-augmentation-system] NASA operates the Global Differential GPS (GDGPS) system, using data from many ground stations located worldwide.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-based-augmentation-system] GDGPS disseminates real-time orbit and clock corrections and supports a wide range of GNSS networks beyond GPS (GLONASS, BeiDou, Galileo, and QZSS).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-based-augmentation-system] WAAS is based on correction data from GDGPS.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-based-augmentation-system] GDGPS is commonly used to generate assisted GNSS data.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-based-augmentation-system] Ground stations are commonly used to accumulate continuous GNSS observations to achieve post-hoc correction of data to the centimeter level.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-based-augmentation-system] Two example systems are the US Continuously Operating Reference Stations (CORS) and the International GNSS Service (IGS).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-based-augmentation-system] In December 2008, the Port Authority of New York and New Jersey invested $2.5 million to install a GBAS at Newark Airport (EWR) with Continental (now United) equipping 15 aircraft for $1.1 million while the FAA committed $2.5 million to assess the technology.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-based-augmentation-system] Honeywell’s SLS-4000 GBAS design was approved by the FAA in September 2009 and is still the only one.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-based-augmentation-system] 1 instrument landings with a 200 ft (61 m) decision height and can be upgraded to a 100 ft (30 m) Cat.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-based-augmentation-system] 2 with real-time monitoring of ionospheric conditions through SBAS, while the more precise Cat.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-based-augmentation-system] 3 SLS-5000 is waiting for compatible airliners.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-based-augmentation-system] The first installations were approved in EWR in 2012 and Houston / IAH in 2013.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-based-augmentation-system] The Port Authority recommends a GBAS for New York JFK and LaGuardia (LGA) to alleviate congestion.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-based-augmentation-system] Newark and Houston GBAS were upgraded to Cat.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-based-augmentation-system] 2, Seattle-Tacoma, San Francisco SFO, JFK and LGA are expected next.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-based-augmentation-system] Airports equipped in Europe are Bremen, Frankfurt, Málaga and Zurich. in Asia-Pacific, airport with installations are Chennai, Kuala Lumpur, Melbourne, Seoul-Gimpo, Shanghai-Pudong and Sydney.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-based-augmentation-system] Helena in the South Atlantic, Punta Cana in the Dominican Republic and Rio de Janeiro–Galeão.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-based-augmentation-system] 1 GBAS landing systems (GLS) installations in Russia with Russian-specific technology.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-based-augmentation-system] In the US, GBAS was previously known as the Local-area augmentation system while a SBAS with a ground references network providing GPS corrections is called WAAS.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-based-augmentation-system] In the US, there were more WAAS LPV approaches reaching 200 ft (61 m) than Cat.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-based-augmentation-system] By Spring 2018, Boeing delivered 3,500 GLS-capable airliners, with 5,000 on order: GLS Cat.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-based-augmentation-system] 2/3 is standard on the Boeing 747-8, 787 and 777 while GLS Cat.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-based-augmentation-system] 1 is optional on the 737NG/MAX and GLS Cat.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-based-augmentation-system] The FAA's NextGen promotes GBAS and GLS to increase airport capacity and to lower noise and weather delays.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-based-augmentation-system] Boeing prefers FAA support than funding while the National Air Traffic Controllers Association argues rigid approaches will lower traffic management flexibility, losing throughput and capacity, a viewpoint shared by Delta Air Lines.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-based-augmentation-system] Some ICAO members vetter GBAS Approach Service Types-D (GAST-D) supporting Cat.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-based-augmentation-system] The US Nationwide Differential GPS System (NDGPS) was an augmentation system for users on U.S. land and waterways.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-based-augmentation-system] It used a ground-based network of radiobeacons.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-based-augmentation-system] The augmentation may also take the form of additional information from navigation sensors being blended into the position calculation, or internal algorithms that improve the navigation performance.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-based-augmentation-system] Many times the additional avionics operate via separate principles from the GNSS and are not necessarily subject to the same sources of error or interference.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-based-augmentation-system] A system such as this is referred to as an aircraft-based augmentation system (ABAS) by the ICAO.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-based-augmentation-system] The most widely used form of ABAS is receiver autonomous integrity monitoring (RAIM), which uses redundant GPS signals to ensure the integrity of the position solution, and to detect faulty signals.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-based-augmentation-system] SBAS and GBAS are key enablers of performance-based navigation (PBN) in aviation.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-based-augmentation-system] SBAS services such as WAAS, EGNOS and MSAS support area navigation (RNAV) and approaches with vertical guidance, including LPV procedures.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-based-augmentation-system] GBAS installations at major airports provide localized corrections that enable highly accurate approach and landing operations on multiple runways from a single ground facility.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-based-augmentation-system] Together, these augmentation systems allow aircraft to fly more precise routes with reduced separation, improved fuel efficiency, and lower environmental impact.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-based-augmentation-system] Apart from government initiatives, the private sector also offers **GNSS correction** services for enhanced precision over a given coverage region, based on techniques such as DGNSS, RTK, and PPP.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-based-augmentation-system] GNSS corrections, sometimes called "L-band corrections", may be provided via communication satellites (typically in geostationary orbit) transmitting in a portion of the L band (1525 MHz to 1560 MHz) not occupied by GNSS signals or, alternatively, over the Internet (in NTRIP format).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] A *satellite-based augmentation system* (SBAS) is a system that is designed to enhance the accuracy of the global GNSS systems.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] The SBAS systems include Japan's QZSS, India's GAGAN, and the European EGNOS, all of them based on GPS.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] Satellite navigation devices determine their location (longitude, latitude, and altitude/elevation) to high precision (within a few centimeters to meters) using time signals transmitted along a line of sight by radio from satellites.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] The system can be used for providing position, navigation or for tracking the position of something fitted with a receiver (satellite tracking).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] The signals also allow the electronic receiver to calculate the current local time to a high precision, which allows time synchronisation.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] These uses are collectively known as **Positioning, Navigation and Timing** (PNT).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] Satnav systems operate independently of any telephonic or internet reception, though these technologies can enhance the usefulness of the positioning information generated.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] Global coverage for each system is generally achieved by a satellite constellation of 18–30 medium Earth orbit (MEO) satellites spread between several orbital planes.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] The actual systems vary, but all use orbital inclinations of >50° and orbital periods of roughly twelve hours (at an altitude of about 20,000 kilometres or 12,000 miles).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] As many of the global GNSS systems (and augmentation systems) use similar frequencies and signals around L1, many "Multi-GNSS" receivers capable of using multiple systems have been produced.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] While some systems strive to interoperate with GPS as well as possible by providing the same clock, others do not.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] Ground-based radio navigation is decades old.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] The DECCA, LORAN, GEE and Omega systems used terrestrial longwave radio transmitters which broadcast a radio pulse from a known "master" location, followed by a pulse repeated from a number of "slave" stations.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] The delay between the reception of the master signal and the slave signals allowed the receiver to deduce the distance to each of the slaves, providing a fix.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] The first satellite navigation system was Transit, a system deployed by the US military in the 1960s.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] Transit's operation was based on the Doppler effect: the satellites travelled on well-known paths and broadcast their signals on a well-known radio frequency.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] The received frequency will differ slightly from the broadcast frequency because of the movement of the satellite with respect to the receiver.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] By monitoring this frequency shift over a short time interval, the receiver can determine its location to one side or the other of the satellite, and several such measurements combined with a precise knowledge of the satellite's orbit can fix a particular position.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] Satellite orbital position errors are caused by radio-wave refraction, gravity field changes (as the Earth's gravitational field is not uniform), and other phenomena.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] A team, led by Harold L Jury of Pan Am Aerospace Division in Florida from 1970 to 1973, found solutions or corrections for many error sources.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] Using real-time data and recursive estimation, the systematic and residual errors were narrowed down to accuracy sufficient for navigation.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] Part of an orbiting satellite's broadcast includes its precise orbital data.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] Originally, the US Naval Observatory (USNO) continuously observed the precise orbits of the GPS.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] As a satellite's orbit deviated, the USNO sent the updated information to the satellite.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] Subsequent broadcasts from an updated satellite would contain its most recent ephemeris.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] The satellite broadcasts a signal that contains orbital data (from which the position of the satellite can be calculated) and the precise time the signal was transmitted.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] Orbital data include a rough almanac for all satellites to aid in finding them, and a precise ephemeris for this satellite (determined with the help of ground stations).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] The orbital ephemeris is transmitted in a data message that is superimposed on a code that serves as a timing reference.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] The satellite uses an atomic clock to maintain synchronization of all the satellites in the constellation.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] The receiver compares the time of broadcast encoded in the transmission of three (at sea level) or four (which allows an altitude calculation also) different satellites, measuring the time-of-flight to each satellite.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] Several such measurements can be made at the same time to different satellites, allowing a continual fix to be generated in real time using an adapted version of trilateration: see GNSS positioning calculation for details.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] Each distance measurement, regardless of the system being used, places the receiver on a spherical shell centred on the broadcaster, at the measured distance from the broadcaster.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] By taking several such measurements and then looking for a point where the shells meet, a fix is generated.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] However, in the case of fast-moving receivers, the position of the receiver moves as signals are received from several satellites.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] In addition, the radio signals slow slightly as they pass through the ionosphere, and this slowing varies with the receiver's angle to the satellite, because that angle corresponds to the distance which the signal travels through the ionosphere.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] The basic computation thus attempts to find the shortest directed line tangent to four oblate spherical shells centred on four satellites.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] Satellite navigation receivers reduce errors by using combinations of signals from multiple satellites and multiple correlators, and then using techniques such as Kalman filtering to combine the noisy, partial, and constantly changing data into a single estimate for position, time, and velocity.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] Einstein's theory of general relativity is applied to GNSS time correction.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] The net result is that time on a GPS satellite clock advances faster than a clock on the ground by about 38 microseconds per day.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] Multiple SatNav systems can be combined in forming a position solution.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] Because the different systems have different time references, the receiver originally needed to estimate one additional inter-system time difference parameter for each additional system added, increasing the number of satellites required for a hybrid position fix.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] Since the early 2010s, a new generation of navigational messages broadcast by many satellites now include "GNSS Time Offset" parameters for converting between time references, allowing receivers to forgo this estimation when needed.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] Broadcast parameters are based on the estimates of the satellite's owners and their accuracy vary across systems.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] The original motivation for satellite navigation was for military applications.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] Satellite navigation allows precision in the delivery of weapons to targets, greatly increasing their lethality whilst reducing inadvertent casualties from mis-directed weapons.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] Satellite navigation also allows forces to be directed and to locate themselves more easily, reducing the fog of war.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] Now a global navigation satellite system, such as Galileo, is used to determine users location and the location of other people or objects at any given moment.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] The range of application of satellite navigation in the future is enormous, including both the public and private sectors across numerous market segments such as science, transport, agriculture, etc.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] The ability to supply satellite navigation signals is also the ability to deny their availability.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] The operator of a satellite navigation system potentially has the ability to degrade or eliminate satellite navigation services over any territory it desires.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] The United States' Global Positioning System (GPS) consists of up to 32 medium Earth orbit satellites in six different orbital planes.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] The exact number of satellites varies as older satellites are retired and replaced.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] Operational since 1978 and globally available since 1994, GPS is the world's most used satellite navigation system.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] The formerly Soviet, and now Russian, *Global'naya Navigatsionnaya Sputnikovaya Sistema*, (Global Navigation Satellite System or GLONASS), is a space-based satellite navigation system that provides a civilian radionavigation-satellite service and is also used by the Russian Aerospace Defence Forces.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] GLONASS has full global coverage since 1995 and with 24 active satellites.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] BeiDou started as the now-decommissioned Beidou-1, an Asia-Pacific local network on the geostationary orbits.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] The second generation of the system BeiDou-2 became operational in China in December 2011.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] The BeiDou-3 system is proposed to consist of 30 MEO satellites and five geostationary satellites (IGSO).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] A 16-satellite regional version (covering Asia and Pacific area) was completed by December 2012.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] Global service was completed by December 2018.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] On 23 June 2020, the BDS-3 constellation deployment is fully completed after the last satellite was successfully launched at the Xichang Satellite Launch Center.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] The European Union and European Space Agency agreed in March 2002 to introduce their own alternative to GPS, called the Galileo positioning system.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] Galileo became operational on 15 December 2016 (global Early Operational Capability, EOC).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] At an estimated cost of €10 billion, the system of 30 MEO satellites was originally scheduled to be operational in 2010.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] The original year to become operational was 2014.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] The first experimental satellite was launched on 28 December 2005.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] Galileo is expected to be compatible with the modernized GPS system.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] The receivers will be able to combine the signals from both Galileo and GPS satellites to greatly increase the accuracy.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] The full Galileo constellation consists of 24 active satellites, the last of which was launched in December 2021.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] The main modulation used in Galileo Open Service signal is the Composite Binary Offset Carrier (CBOC) modulation.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] The **NavIC** (Navigation with Indian Constellation) is an autonomous regional satellite navigation system developed by the Indian Space Research Organisation (ISRO).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] The Indian government approved the project in May 2006.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] It consists of a constellation of seven navigational satellites.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] Three of the satellites are placed in geostationary orbit (GEO) and the remaining four in geosynchronous orbit (GSO) to have a larger signal footprint and lower number of satellites to map the region.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] It is intended to provide an all-weather absolute position accuracy of better than 7.6 metres (25 ft) throughout India and within a region extending approximately 1,500 km (900 mi) around it.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] An Extended Service Area lies between the primary service area and a rectangle area enclosed by the 30th parallel south to the 50th parallel north and the 30th meridian east to the 130th meridian east, 1,500 to 6,000 km (900 to 3,700 mi) beyond borders.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] A goal of complete Indian control has been stated, with the space segment, ground segment and user receivers all being built in India.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] The constellation was in orbit as of 2018, and the system was available for public use in early 2018.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] NavIC provides two levels of service, the "standard positioning service", which will be open for civilian use, and a "restricted service" (an encrypted one) for authorized users (including military).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] There are plans to expand NavIC system by increasing constellation size from 7 to 11.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] India plans to make the NavIC global by adding 24 more MEO satellites.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] The Global NavIC will be free to use for the global public.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] The first two generations of China's BeiDou navigation system were designed to provide regional coverage.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] The Quasi-Zenith Satellite System (QZSS) is a four-satellite regional time transfer system and enhancement for GPS covering Japan and the Asia-Oceania regions.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] QZSS services were available on a trial basis as of January 12, 2018, and were started in November 2018.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] The first satellite was launched in September 2010.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] An independent satellite navigation system (from GPS) with 7 satellites is planned for 2023.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] The European Geostationary Navigation Overlay Service (EGNOS) is a satellite-based augmentation system (SBAS) developed by the European Space Agency and Eurocontrol on behalf of the European Commission.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] Currently, it supplements GPS by reporting on the reliability and accuracy of their positioning data and sending out corrections.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] The system will supplement Galileo in the future version 3.0.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] EGNOS consists of 40 Ranging Integrity Monitoring Stations, 2 Mission Control Centres, 6 Navigation Land Earth Stations, the EGNOS Wide Area Network (EWAN), and 3 geostationary satellites.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] Ground stations determine the accuracy of the satellite navigation systems data and transfer it to the geostationary satellites; users may freely obtain this data from those satellites using an EGNOS-enabled receiver, or over the Internet.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] One main use of the system is in aviation.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] According to specifications, horizontal position accuracy when using EGNOS-provided corrections should be better than seven metres.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] In practice, the horizontal position accuracy is at the metre level.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] Similar service is provided in North America by the Wide Area Augmentation System (WAAS), in Russia by the System for Differential Corrections and Monitoring (SDCM), and in Asia, by Japan's Multi-functional Satellite Augmentation System (MSAS) and India's GPS-aided GEO augmented navigation (GAGAN).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] Galileo and EGNOS received a budget of €14.6 billion for its six-year, 2021–2027, research and development period.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] Using multiple GNSS systems for user positioning increases the number of visible satellites, improves precise point positioning (PPP) and shortens the average convergence time.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] The signal-in-space ranging error (SISRE) in November 2019 were 1.6 cm for Galileo, 2.3 cm for GPS, 5.2 cm for GLONASS and 5.5 cm for BeiDou when using real-time corrections for satellite orbits and clocks.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] The average SISREs of the BDS-3 MEO, IGSO, and GEO satellites were 0.52 m, 0.90 m and 1.15 m, respectively.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] Compared to the four major global satellite navigation systems consisting of MEO satellites, the SISRE of the BDS-3 MEO satellites was slightly inferior to 0.4 m of Galileo, slightly superior to 0.59 m of GPS, and remarkably superior to 2.33 m of GLONASS.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] The SISRE of BDS-3 IGSO was 0.90 m, which was on par with the 0.92 m of QZSS IGSO.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] However, as the BDS-3 GEO satellites were newly launched and not completely functioning in orbit, their average SISRE was marginally worse than the 0.91 m of the QZSS GEO satellites.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] Doppler Orbitography and Radio-Positioning Integrated by Satellite (DORIS) is a French precision navigation system.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] Unlike other GNSS systems, it is based on static emitting stations around the world, the receivers being on satellites, in order to precisely determine their orbital position.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] The system may be used also for mobile receivers on land with more limited usage and coverage.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] The two current operational low Earth orbit (LEO) satellite phone networks are able to track transceiver units with accuracy of a few kilometres using doppler shift calculations from the satellite.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] The coordinates are sent back to the transceiver unit where they can be read using AT commands or a graphical user interface.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] This can also be used by the gateway to enforce restrictions on geographically bound calling plans.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] The International Telecommunication Union (ITU) defines a **radionavigation-satellite service** (**RNSS**) as "a radiodetermination-satellite service used for the purpose of radionavigation.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] This service may also include feeder links necessary for its operation".
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] RNSS is regarded as a safety-of-life service and an essential part of navigation which must be protected from interferences.
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] The allocation of radio frequencies is provided according to *Article 5* of the ITU Radio Regulations (edition 2012).
[src:gnss-positioning-deep/satellite-navigation] To improve harmonisation in spectrum usage, most service allocations are incorporated in national Tables of Frequency Allocations and Utilisations within the responsibility of the appropriate national administration.
